    "body": "@alexcrichton  Right, I overlooked this notice\n\n> The number of bytes read may be less than the number requested, even 0.\n\nin http://doc.rust-lang.org/std/io/trait.Reader.html#tymethod.read and that `read_at_least()` was responsible for looping until the `buf.len()`-th byte.  (The name sounds odd to me because it implies more than `len()` bytes might be read.)\n\nHowever I don't quite understand why there should exist such an asymmetry between reading (`read()` or `read_at_least()`) and writing(`write()`.)   On a pipe, for example, write operation as well as read operation can return before reaching the `len()`-th byte and can block.\n\nI'd like to propose to split `read()` into `read() -> IoResult<uint>` and `read_at_least()`\n",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
